{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489161"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:07:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:07:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"606"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/606"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.01,0.79,0.09,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"606"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110865"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/606"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"606"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93035"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"207"},{"type":"tags","id":"477"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"2149"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41890"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43802"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110865"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man is reviewed on the surgical ward three days after admission for upper gastrointestinal bleeding from a gastric ulcer, which was managed surgically. He has a medical history of osteoarthritis, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and peptic ulcer disease. His regular medications include paracetamol, omeprazole and fluticasone/umeclidinium/vilanterol inhaler. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and reports drinking five to six standard drinks of alcohol daily. He has been receiving intravenous thiamine 100 mg daily since admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOvernight, nursing staff report he has become irritable, confused, and has been telling them that \u0022aeroplanes have crashed in his room\u0022. On examination, he appears diaphoretic with visible tremor of his hands. He is not oriented to time nor place and refuses physical examination. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 160/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.3\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alcohol-induced psychotic disorder","Opioid toxicity","Delirium tremens","Post-operative delirium","Wernicke encephalopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with confusion, hallucinations, tremor, and autonomic instability three days after hospital admission, in the context of a significant alcohol history. Delirium tremens is a severe form of alcohol withdrawal that typically occurs 48-72 hours after cessation of alcohol intake in people with alcohol dependence. It is characterised by altered mental status, autonomic hyperactivity, and perceptual disturbances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelirium tremens\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the timing (three days post-admission), the constellation of symptoms (confusion, visual hallucinations, tremor, tachycardia, hypertension, fever), and the patient\u0027s history of daily alcohol consumption. The vivid visual hallucinations (\u0022aeroplanes crashing\u0022) are particularly characteristic. This is a medical emergency requiring prompt treatment with benzodiazepines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol-induced psychotic disorder\u003C/strong\u003E can occur during chronic alcohol use or withdrawal but typically presents with hallucinations in clear consciousness without the disorientation, autonomic instability, and tremor seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioid toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E would present with respiratory depression, miosis, and decreased level of consciousness rather than the hyperadrenergic state observed. While opioids may have been used post-operatively, the clinical picture is inconsistent with opioid overdose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-operative delirium\u003C/strong\u003E can occur after surgery, particularly in older patients, but the specific combination of visual hallucinations, tremor, and autonomic instability in a patient with significant alcohol history makes delirium tremens more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by thiamine deficiency and presents with the classic triad of confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia. While this patient is at risk given his alcohol history, he has been receiving thiamine supplementation, and the presentation with hallucinations, tremor, and autonomic instability is more consistent with delirium tremens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Delirium tremens is a severe alcohol withdrawal syndrome characterised by confusion, hallucinations, tremor and autonomic instability, occurring 2-3 days after alcohol cessation.","Delirium tremens is a medical emergency that requires prompt recognition and treatment with benzodiazepines to prevent complications.","Risk factors for delirium tremens include heavy alcohol use, abrupt cessation, and concurrent medical illness."],"references":["Haber P, Lintzeris N, Proude E, Lopatko O. Guidelines for the Treatment of Alcohol Problems [online]. In: Australian Government Department of Health and Ageing. 2009. Available at: https://alcoholtreatmentguidelines.com.au/pdf/guidelines-for-the-treatment-of-alcohol-problems.pdf","Management of patients at risk of alcohol withdrawal in acute hospitals Policy Guideline.\u00a0In: South Australia: Drug and Alcohol Services South Australia (DASSA) [online]. 2016. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/7ded16804c937bcd84138c6fd538dbf3/Management+of+patients+at+risk+of+alcohol+withdrawal+in+acute+hospitals+Clinical+Guideline.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-7ded16804c937bcd84138c6fd538dbf3-oqBoG0H","Reddy S, Irkal J, Srinivasamurthy A. Postoperative delirium in elderly citizens and current practice.\u00a0J Anaesthesiol Clin Pharmacol. 2017;33(3):291-299. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5672535/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93035"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"606"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93035"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-04T18:41:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-04T18:44:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"606"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110865"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterol